;; PgBouncer auth file — copy to `userlist.txt` and edit, then place the SAME file
;; on all three database hosts. (userlist.txt is git-ignored so the secret never
;; gets committed; this .example is the template.)
;;
;; Format:  "username" "secret"
;;
;; ── EASIEST (recommended) ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Paste the crimson application password — the CRIMSON_APP_PASSWORD from your
;; postgres-ha/.env, i.e. the same password in your app's DATABASE_URL — in plain
;; text between the quotes below. auth_type is scram-sha-256 (see pgbouncer.ini),
;; so PgBouncer derives the SCRAM handshake from this to BOTH verify the app
;; client and log in to PostgreSQL. This password already lives in .env on these
;; same hosts, so the file adds no new exposure. Then lock it down: chmod 600.
;;
;; ── MORE SECURE (optional) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
;; Store the one-way SCRAM *verifier* instead of the plaintext password — see
;; README §5 for the single read-only command that prints the exact line. Replace
;; the line below with what it prints (it starts with SCRAM-SHA-256$...).

"crimson" "REPLACE_WITH_YOUR_CRIMSON_APP_PASSWORD"
